## Essence First (1 paragraph)
Buoyancy control is the skill of making your body neither sink nor float—called neutral buoyancy—so you can hover where you want in the water. You do this with three tools: weights (lead that makes you sink), your BCD (Buoyancy Control Device—an air bladder that makes you float), and your breath (your lungs act like a tiny, instant buoyancy adjuster). The purpose is simple: move safely, save air, protect the reef, and enjoy the dive. It comes from basic physics: as you go deeper air spaces shrink (you get heavier), and as you rise they expand (you get lighter). Good buoyancy matters because it prevents runaway ascents/descents, reduces fatigue, improves trim (your body’s orientation in the water), and keeps your fins off the bottom.

## Core Framework (3–5 items)
- Name: Right Weight First
  - Explanation: Carry only enough lead to end the dive neutral at 5 m/15 ft with 50 bar/500 psi and an empty BCD.
  - Real-world example: At the surface with near-empty tank, you float at eye level holding a normal breath and slowly sink when you fully exhale.
  - Why it matters / common pitfall: Too much lead forces you to stuff air in the BCD (yo-yo depth); too little lead makes you bob up on the safety stop.

- Name: BCD = Big Moves, Breath = Fine Moves
  - Explanation: Use small, 1-second BCD bursts and venting for depth changes; use slow breathing to fine-tune and hover.
  - Real-world example: Add a short puff to stop a slow descent, then use gentle inhales/exhales to stay level.
  - Why it matters / common pitfall: Overusing the BCD causes overshoot; trying to “breath-only dive” fails if weighting is wrong.

- Name: Pause–Assess–Correct (PAC)
  - Explanation: When depth drifts, pause, check if you’re rising or sinking, then correct with the smallest tool that works.
  - Real-world example: Notice you’re rising, exhale fully, then vent a little; if still rising, vent the BCD again.
  - Why it matters / common pitfall: Acting without pausing leads to over-correction and yo-yoing.

- Name: Trim and Stillness
  - Explanation: Stay horizontal, knees slightly bent, hands still, slow kicks—streamlined gear and stillness reduce lift/sink surprises.
  - Real-world example: Tuck hoses, shift tank to balance, hover with ankles crossed and no hand sculling.
  - Why it matters / common pitfall: Poor trim makes your fins push you up/down; constant hand use masks true buoyancy.

- Name: Anticipate Expansion
  - Explanation: Air expands on ascent (Boyle’s Law), so start venting early and often as you get shallower.
  - Real-world example: On ascent, hold your deflator high and tap vent every 1–2 m/3–6 ft to control speed.
  - Why it matters / common pitfall: Waiting too long to vent causes runaway ascents; never hold your breath.

## Story / Analogy
Imagine you’re balancing a backpack helium balloon, a small elevator, and your own breathing on a floating walkway. The backpack (weights) sets your baseline—too heavy and you’re glued down, too light and you can’t stay put. The elevator (BCD) does the bigger up/down moves—tap to go up a floor, tap to go down, never jam the button.

Your breath is the feather touch—tiny, smooth inhales lift you a little; slow, long exhales settle you a little. When the walkway slopes (depth changes), the balloon changes size (air expansion), so you anticipate and ease the elevator down as you approach the top. Pause, see what’s happening, make the smallest correction, and you’ll glide.

